      "content": "When I said \"culturally insensitive,\" I meant that you should be aware of and adapt to local customs, but not be bound by them. A sophisticated global professional knows how to navigate different environments while maintaining a level of elegance and poise. For instance, in Japan, it's customary to wait for the host to start eating before you begin, but in the US, it's generally acceptable to start eating as soon as the food is placed in front of you.\n\nIn terms of dining, a universal standard is to use a napkin, keep your elbows off the table, and not speak with your mouth full. When speaking in a meeting, it's best to avoid loud or aggressive tone, and to listen more than you speak. A sophisticated professional also knows how to make small talk, but not overdo it. A good rule of thumb is to ask open-ended questions and listen actively, rather than dominating the conversation.\n\nAs for dress code, the key is to look polished and put-together, without drawing attention to yourself. A simple, elegant watch, a quality belt, and a classic handbag or briefcase are all good investments. And of course, a sophisticated professional always knows how to make a good first impression, whether it",
